# 7.1 Sync To Repo

## **7.1 Sync To Repo**

The **Sync To Repo** feature enables seamless integration of your API specifications (OAS) with external source code repositories such as **GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, Azure Repos, or AWS CodeCommit**. This ensures version control, collaboration, and backup of API designs. By syncing directly with a repository, teams can manage changes, track revisions, and collaborate effectively within their preferred DevOps workflow.

```
Best Practice:
Configure Sync to Repo after the OAS is finalized and ready. Although you can enable sync at any time, it is recommended to configure it only after the Swagger is complete to avoid unnecessary commits and rework.
```

* Click the **Sync to Repo** icon (represented as a connected-node symbol) on the right side of the screen (see Figure 7.1a). 

![][image2]  
***Figure 7.1a: Sync to Repo icon***

* The system opens the **Sync To Repo** panel on the right side of the design canvas (see Figure 7.1b).

![][image3]  
***Figure 7.1b: Sync to Repo panel***

#### **Sync To Repo Panel:** 

#### The **Sync To Repo** panel allows you to connect and sync your **OAS (OpenAPI Specification)** with an external source code repository.

* **Source:**  
  * Select the repository provider where you want to sync your OAS.  
  * Options: **GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, Azure, AWS CodeCommit**.  
  * Example: If your project is hosted on GitHub, select **GitHub**.  
* **Repo Name\*** (Required):   
  * Enter the repository name where the API specification will be synced.  
  * Example: flight-management-api-repo  
* **Branch\*** (Required):   
  * Specify the branch within the repository.  
  * Example: main or develop  
* **Host Url\*** (Required):  
  * Enter the Git server URL of your repository.  
  * Example: [https://github.com/apiwiz/flight-management-api-repo.git](https://github.com/apiwiz/flight-management-api-repo.git)  
* **Folder Name\*** (Required):  
  * Specify the **folder path within the repository** where the API specification will be stored. Use **/** to store the specification in the **root directory**.  
  * Example: api-specs/v1  
* **Commit Message \*** (Required):  
  * Enter a commit message to describe the change being pushed to the repository.  
  * Example: Added new flight booking API specification  
* **SSL (Enable)**:  
  * A Checkbox option to enable SSL for secure communication with the repository server.  
* **Authentication:** The Authentication section ensures secure access when connecting to external repositories. You can authenticate using one of two methods:  
  * **Token Authentication:** Use a personal access token generated from your repository platform (for example, GitHub or GitLab).  
    * **Username** (Required): Enter the repository account username.  
    * **Token** (Required): Enter the personal access token.  
    * For example: Username –  api-admin-user and Token: ghp\_a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8i9j90hui0 (GitHub Personal Access Token)

**Note:** For instructions on generating or accessing a token in GitHub, see [Managing your personal access tokens.](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/managing-your-personal-access-tokens)

* #### **Password Authentication:** Use your repository account credentials for login.

  * #### **Username** (Required): Enter the repository account username.

    * #### **Password** (Required): Enter the repository account password.

    * #### For example: Username: dev-user and Password: mypassword123

* After entering all required details, click the **Save** icon (represented as a floppy-disk symbol) on the right side of the **Sync To Repo** panel to complete the configuration.

# 7.2 Commit History

## **7.2 Commit History**

The **Commit History** panel provides a chronological record of all revisions and updates made to an API specification (OAS). It enables teams to track changes, review statuses, and maintain version control for better collaboration and governance.

* Click the **Commit History** icon represented as a branching tree symbol) on the right side of the design canvas (see Figure 7.2a). 

![][image4]  
***Figure 7.2a: Commit History icon***

* The system opens the **Commit History** panel on the right side (see Figure 7.2b).

![][image5]  
***Figure 7.2b: Commit History panel***

### **Commit History form – History Section**

The **History** section displays the **status change history** of the selected OAS revision in **chronological order**. Each entry includes the following details:

* **Date and Timestamp:**  
  * Displays the date and time when the revision was created or last updated. Subsequent changes reflect **user actions** and **status updates**.  
  * Example: 2025 Sep 12 15:14  
* **Action Performed:**  
  * Describes the activity associated with the status change, such as:  
  * Example: “approved after review” – indicates the specification was reviewed and approved.  
* **User:**  
  * Shows the name of the user who performed the action.  
  * Example: ABC DXY  
* **Status:**   
  * The **Status** field indicates the current state of the revision. This helps users track the progress and lifecycle of an API specification.  
  * Example: **Approved**: The revision has been reviewed and approved.

**Note:** There are five possible statuses.

* **Draft** – The revision is in draft mode and has not yet been finalised.

* **Review** – The revision has been submitted for review and is awaiting feedback or approval.  
* **Approved** – The revision has been reviewed and approved for further use.  
* **Deprecate** – The revision is marked for deprecation and should not be used for new implementations.  
* **Retired** – The revision is retired and no longer in use.  
* **Change Required** – The revision needs modifications before it can be approved.




# 7.3 Swagger Reviews

## **7.3 Swagger Reviews**

The **Swagger Reviews feature** enables collaborative review of an API specification by allowing reviewers and authors to exchange feedback directly within the OAS design canvas. This feature supports adding, replying to, and deleting comments, while also notifying stakeholders through email alerts. It streamlines the review process, improves communication, and maintains a clear history of discussions for each revision.

* Click the **Comments icon** (represented as a speech bubble) on the right side of the design canvas (see Figure 7.3a).

![][image6]  
***Figure 7.3a: Comment icon***

* The **Comments panel** opens on the right, displaying existing comments and an option to add new ones (as shown in Figure 7.3b).

![][image7]  
***Figure 7.3b: Comments Panel***

**Swagger Reviews panel** 

The **Comments panel** allows reviewers and authors to collaborate by adding feedback, questions, and suggestions directly within the OAS design canvas. This ensures all discussions remain contextually tied to the API specification.

**Adding a Comment**

1. Click **\+ Add Comment** at the top of the panel (as shown in Figure 7.3b).  
2. Type your feedback, questions, clarification, or suggestion in the text field.  
3. Click **Save** to add the comment, or click **Cancel** to discard it (as shown in Figure 7.3c).  
4. The system also sends an **email notification** to the OAS developer whenever a new comment is added, ensuring timely awareness and follow-up.

![][image8]

***Figure 7.3c: Add comment***

**Replying to a Comment**

* Click the **Reply** button below an existing comment.  
* Enter your response in the text box.  
* Click **Save** to post your reply, or click **Cancel** to discard it.  
* Replies are **nested under the original comment**, keeping discussions organized and easy to follow. (as shown in Figure 7.3d).  
* The system also sends an **email notification** to the relevant user when a reply is added.

![][image9].***Figure 7.3d: Reply comment***

**Tracking Comments** 

* Each comment entry includes:  
  * **Reviewer name** – who added the comment.  
  * **Timestamp** – when the comment was posted.  
  * **Comment text** – the actual feedback.  
* Comments appear directly in the panel for centralised tracking (see Figure 7.3e).

![][image10]

***Figure 7.3e: Viewing comments***

**Deleting Comments**

* Click the three-elliptical dot (⋮) menu next to a comment.  
* Select **Delete** to permanently remove the comment (as shown in Figure 7.3f).

**![][image11]**

***Figure 7.3f: Deleting comments***

* After deletion, the system displays a confirmation success message.

# 7.4 Associated Teams

## **7.4 Associated Teams**

**Associate Teams** in OAS enables you to link an API specification with one or more organisational teams. This feature establishes ownership, ensures accountability, and promotes collaborative development and review of the specification. By associating teams, you provide clear visibility into who manages the API, simplify communication across contributors, and support effective governance of API lifecycle activities.

```
Note:
You can create and manage teams from the Settings module. Teams created here become available for association in the Associate Teams panel of an OAS.
For detailed instructions on managing teams, see Manage Teams in the Settings section.
```

* Click the **Teams icon** (represented as a group of two user figures) located on the right side of the design canvas (as shown in Figure 7.4a).

![][image12]  
***Figure 7.4a: Teams icon***

* The system displays the **Associate Teams form** on the right side of the screen (see Figure 7.4b).

![][image13]  
***Figure 7.4b: Teams Panel***

**Associate Teams**   
The **Associate Teams** form allows you to link an API specification (OAS) with one or more teams in your organization. Associating teams ensures proper ownership, collaboration, and accountability for the specification.

Each entry in the panel displays the following details:

* **Name** – The name of the team.Example: Developer Team, Backend Team.  
* **Members** – The number of members in the team.Example: Developer Team – Members: 3\.  
* **Description** – A short description of the team, if available.Example: Backend-team – desc: Backend-team.  
* **Toggle Button** – Lets you associate or disassociate the team with the selected OAS.  
  * **Enabled (blue):** The team is associated.  
  * **Disabled (grey):** The team is not associated.  
* After enabling (associating) the required teams, click the **Save** icon (represented as a floppy-disk symbol) located at the top-right corner of the Teams panel to apply the changes.  
* Alternatively, you can associate teams by navigating to **Settings → OAS → Configure OAS** and selecting the required teams from there.

#### For Example:

* In the Figure 7.4b, the Developer Team (3 members) and SpecDelete team are associated with the Flight Management API.  
* Teams like teamName and Backend-team are listed but not associated.

# 7.5 Associated Products

## **7.5 Associated Products**

The **Associate Products** feature allows you to link an API specification (OAS) with one or more business products in your organization. Associating products helps establish clear alignment between APIs and the business capabilities or services they represent. This ensures traceability, simplifies management, and supports better product-level governance.

* Click the **Associate Products icon** (represented as a 3D cube inside a bounding box) (see Figure 7.5a).

![][image14]  
***Figure 7.5a: Associate Products icon***

* The panel opens on the right side of the design canvas (as shown in Figure 7.5b).

![][image15]  
***Figure 7.5b: Products panel***

**Products Panel**

The Products panel displays available product and provides options to associate them with the current OAS. The panel provides the following fields and options:

* **Tagged:**  
  * Displays the products currently associated with the API specification. Example: apiwiz.  
  * You can add or remove product tags as needed.  
* **Products**  
  * Lists all available products in your organization.  
  * Each product has a checkbox to enable or disable association.Example: CreditCard.  
* **Toggle (Checkbox)**  
  * Checked: Associates the product with the selected OAS.  
  * Unchecked: Removes the association.  
* After tagging (attaching) the required products, click the **Save icon** (represented as a floppy-disk symbol) located at the top-right corner of the **Associate Products** panel. This confirms the association and updates the OAS metadata.  
* For example:

In Figure 7.5b, the **Flight Management API** is already tagged with the product **apiwiz**. You can additionally associate it with **CreditCard** by selecting the checkbox.

***Note:***

You can create and manage products from the **Connectors module**. Products created here become available for association in the **Products panel** of an OAS.

For detailed instructions on managing partners, see [**Manage Products**](https://docs-developer-dev-docs.apiwiz.io/guides/N4IgDghgLgFgggJwOYGcQC5QEsAmGQBsAHDgTgAwAsBAZgEYQCsJOjOlzAzJeQJwgBfADQgA9rACmCRKgygoWKABsJ+OAAUAkgHcsALwAEmgHZQJSBNCyjjIEUgCuuCZrzpCRIuXIB2AhD8CcgBjIkZgzh8aACYIAEYvO3AIJBc3EABHADklAAkiOgB5YKQAdQBPUsYAGQARCQAlAE0AUTgsJJwJFGCELDAFG3xBASA#manage-products) in the **APIwiz Integration** section of the **Connectors Module Documentation**.

**Accessing Manage Products**

1. Navigate to the **Connectors** module.  
2. Under **APIwiz Integration**, select **Manage Products**.  
3. Click **View Details**.  
4. The **Manage Products panel** appears on the right side of the screen (see Figure 7.5c).

![][image16]

***Figure 7.5b: Manage Products panel***

**Manage Products panel**

**Manage Products** allows you to define reusable product groups that organize APIs by business context (for example, CreditCard, Lending, Payments). Each product created here can later be tagged to one or more OAS specifications. The panel provides the following fields and options:

1. **Add New Product:**  
* Use the **\+ icon** at the top-right of the panel to add multiple products.  
* **Product Name**\* (Required): A required field where you enter the name of the product.  
* Each added row includes a Product Name field.  
* Example: apiwiz, CreditCard.  
2. **Delete Product:** Use the **Trash icon** next to a product entry to remove it.  
3. **Save / Cancel** (located at the bottom-right corner)  
* **Save**: Stores all added or updated products.  
* **Cancel**: Discards unsaved changes.

Example:

In Figure 7.5c, two products are added: *apiwiz* and *CreditCard*. A new product is being created in the third *Product Name* field. Once you click **Save**, these products will be available for tagging in the Products panel of an OAS.

# 7.6 Associated Partners

## **7.6 Associated Partners**

The **Associate Partners** feature in OAS allows you to link an API specification with specific business partners. Associating partners ensures clear visibility of external or internal stakeholders involved in using or collaborating on the API. It also helps in partner-specific governance, accountability, and tracking.

### **Tagging a Partner** 

* Partner tagging is mandatory to make an API visible in the Developer Portal.  
* Every user in the Developer Portal is associated with either an internal or external partner.  
* An OAS is visible only to users who belong to the partner tagged to that OAS.  
* If a Swagger is not tagged to a partner, it will not be visible in the Developer Portal.  
* When creating an application, viewing API References, or accessing API Guides, users can see only the APIs that are tagged to their associated partner.  
* This ensures controlled access, partner-specific visibility, and secure API exposure.

In the design canvas, click the **Associate Partners** icon (represented as a handshake symbol) on the right side panel (see Figure 7.6a)  
![][image17]  
***Figure 7.6a: Partners icon*** 

* The **Partners** panel opens on the right side of the canvas (as shown in Figure 7.6b).

![][image18]  
***Figure 7.6b: Partners Panel*** 

**Partners Panel** 

The **Partners** panel displays available partner groups and provides options to associate them with the current OAS. Each entry in the panel includes:

* **Tagged**  
  * Displays all currently associated partners.Example: Internal, Trusted Partner.  
* **Partners**  
  * Displays the list of all available partners that can be associated. Example: External, new\_partner\_1, test, open banking.  
* **Selection Checkbox**  
  * Allows you to tag (associate) or untag (disassociate) a partner with the selected OAS.  
  * **Checked** – The partner is associated with the OAS.  
  * **Unchecked**  – The partner is not associated.  
* After selecting or deselecting partners, click the **Save** icon (represented as a floppy-disk symbol) in the top-right corner of the panel to confirm your changes.  
* For Example: In Figure 7.6b, the **Internal** and **Trusted Partner** partners are associated with the *Flight Management API*.

***Note:***

You can create and manage partners from the **Connectors** module. Partners created here become available for association in the **Partners** form of an OAS.

For detailed instructions on managing partners, see [**Manage Partners**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/12hld0_SKZnInKUpaeWvI7st5M6B3dt7qHys6S3u2Wwk/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.yqavg6708hq4) in the **APIwiz Integration** section of the **Connectors Module Documentation**.

### **Impact of Removing a Partner**

* When a partner is **removed from an OAS**, users associated with that partner **will no longer be able to view the OAS** in the Developer Portal.  
* The API is immediately **hidden from all partner group users** who are no longer tagged.  
* This affects visibility in:  
  * **Application creation**  
  * **API References**  
  * **API Guides**

# 7.8 Compare Changes

## **7.8 Compare Changes**

The **Compare Changes** section enables you to view and analyze the differences between two revisions of an **OpenAPI Specification (OAS)**. This feature helps reviewers and developers track modifications, validate updates, and ensure consistency across revisions.

***Note:*** The **Compare Changes** option appears on the right side of the OAS design window only when there are two or more revisions available.

Click the **Compare Changes icon** (represented by a cube inside a frame) on the right side of the design canvas (see Figure 7.7a)

![][image19]  
***Figure 7.7a: Compare changes icon*** 

* The system opens the **Compare Revisions** panel at the bottom of the screen (see Figure 7.7b).

![][image20]  
***Figure 7.7b: Compare Revisions panel***

**Compare Revisions Panel**

In OAS, **Compare Changes** enables users to evaluate differences between two revisions of a specification. This ensures transparency, simplifies version control, and supports collaborative review by making changes explicit. The panel displays two sections side by side:

1. **Current Revision** – Shows the latest saved revision of the OAS. Example: *Revision 4* (Current Revision)  
2. **Previous Revision** – Allows you to select a prior revision for comparison. Example: *Revision 3* (Older Revision) Use the dropdown menu to select the revision you want to compare with the current revision.

### **Features**

* **Side-by-Side Comparison** – Displays the OAS specifications from two revisions in parallel, highlighting differences in content such as:

  * Title  
  * Description  
  * Contact details  
  * Version  
  * Paths and operations  
* **Scroll Synchronization** – Both revision windows scroll in sync, making it easier to track changes line by line.  
* **Change Tracking** – Modifications between revisions (such as updates to metadata, endpoints, or parameters) are clearly visible for review.  
* **Color-Coded Highlights** (see Figure 7.6b):  
  * **Red Highlight** – Indicates deletions or elements removed from the current revision.  
  * **Green Highlight** – Indicates additions or elements introduced in the current revision.

***Figure 7.7b: Colour-Coded Highlights***
